{"title_page": "Edward G. Lengel", "text_new": "{{Infobox writer\n| embed            = \n| honorific_prefix = \n| name             = Edward G. Lengel\n| honorific_suffix = \n| image            = \n| image_size       = \n| image_upright    = \n| alt              = \n| caption          = \n| native_name      = \n| native_name_lang = \n| pseudonym        = \n| birth_name       = \n| birth_date       = {{Birth date and age|1968|08|09}}\n| birth_place      = \n| death_date       = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| death_place      = \n| resting_place    = \n| occupation       = \n| language         = \n| residence        = \n| nationality      = \n| citizenship      = \n| education        = \n| alma_mater       = \n| period           = \n| genre            = military history<br>\n| subject          = <!-- or: | subjects = -->\n| movement         = \n| notableworks     = ''General George Washington: A Military Life''\n| spouse           = <!-- or: | spouses = -->\n| partner          = <!-- or: | partners = -->\n| children         = \n| relatives        = \n| awards           = a co-recipient of the [[National Humanities Medal]] (for his work on the George Washington Papers project)<br>\n| signature        = \n| signature_alt    = \n| years_active     = \n| module           = \n| website          = <!-- {{URL|example.org}} -->\n| portaldisp       = <!-- \"on\", \"yes\", \"true\", etc; or omit -->\n}}\n\n'''Edward \"Ed\" G. Lengel''' (born August 9, 1968) is an [[United States|American]] author and military historian. He is the 2018 Revolutionary in Residence for [[Colonial Williamsburg]].<ref name=\"Edward G. Lengel\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.colonialwilliamsburg.com/learn/revolutionaries-in-residence/ed-lengel|title=Edward G. Lengel|access-date=2018-04-26}}</ref> His previously published books focus on George Washington's life and legacy, and World War I.\n\nHe is a co-recipient of the [[National Humanities Medal]] (for his work on the George Washington Papers project), and his books have been honored with the [[Army Historical Foundation]] Distinguished Book Award, the Norman B. Tomlinson, Jr. prize, and other awards. He is the author of ''General George Washington: A Military Life'',<ref>{{cite news|last=Berthel|first=Ron|title=New books profile first U.S. president -- and first first lady|url=http://helenair.com/lifestyles/article_6f03424b-c6f5-5c6e-9224-7e82a40df028.html|accessdate=3 March 2011|newspaper=[[Independent Record]]|date=16 July 2005}}</ref> which was a finalist for the 2006 [[George Washington Book Prize]], and his 2018 release ''Never in Finer Company: The Men of the Great War\u2019s Lost Battalion''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.edwardlengel.com/portfolio/282/|title=Never in Finer Company: The Men of the Great War's Lost Battalion \u2013 Edward Lengel|work=Edward Lengel|access-date=2018-04-26|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n== Personal background ==\nEdward G. Lengel was born on August 9, 1968, in Washington, D.C. His father Alan was an elementary school teacher; his mother Shelbia (n\u00e9e: Looper) worked for the Department of Health and Human Services. Lengel has one sibling, Eric Lengel.\n\nLengel received a B.A. in history in 1991 from [[George Mason University]] in Fairfax, Virginia. In 1993, he completed an M.A. in history with the [[University of Virginia]], going on to acquire a Ph.D. from the same university in modern European history in 1998. The title of his dissertation was: ''A 'Perverse and Ill-Fated People': British Perceptions of the Irish, 1840\u20131860''.\n\nLengel describes his work as, \u201ca storyteller, seeking to unfold history\u2019s human core by walking through ancient lands, sites and battlefields in my own hiking boots.\u201d<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.edwardlengel.com/about/|title=About \u2013 Edward Lengel|work=Edward Lengel|access-date=2018-04-26|language=en-US}}</ref> Consequently, Lengel conducts and participates in hiking tours, including leading independent tours, and providing annual conference tours with America's History, LLC.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://americashistoryllc.com/2018/loyalists-vs-patriots-the-road-to-victory-from-musgroves-mill-to-cowpens-august-1780-january-1781/|title=Loyalists vs. Patriots: The Road to Victory from  Musgrove\u2019s Mill to Cowpens, August 1780-January 1781 (September 12-15, 2018)|date=2018-03-06|work=americashistoryllc.com|access-date=2018-04-26|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nLengel is engaged to Caitlin Conley, a research historian and cellist originally from Colorado Springs, Colorado. Lengel has two children from a previous marriage.\n\n== Professional background ==\nWhile working on his B.A., Lengel worked at the [[George Mason University]] Law Library, 1990\u20131991. Lengel began his professional career at the University of Virginia. From his beginnings as a research assistant in the University of Virginia Library, he rose to become an Assistant Professor and Assistant Editor in 1997 on the George Washington Papers Project.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.linkedin.com/in/edward-lengel-23598097/|title=Edward Lengel, LinkedIn Profile/Resum\u00e9|last=Edward|first=Lengel|date=April 26, 2018|website=linkedin.com/in/edward-lengel-23598097/}}</ref>\n\nFrom 2010\u20132016 he was Professor and Director of the project that he renamed the Washington Papers Project.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://augustafreepress.com/university-of-virginia-to-publish-rare-letters-of-first-lady-martha-washington/|title=University of Virginia to publish rare letters of First Lady Martha Washington|last=AFP|date=2015-05-02|work=Augusta Free Press|access-date=2018-04-26|language=en-US}}</ref> During Lengel's tenure, he oversaw the creation of the Barbados Diary, Martha Washington Papers and Washington Family Papers projects,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/grade-point/wp/2015/04/28/after-george-washington-died-his-wife-burned-her-letters-except-these/|title=After George Washington died, his wife burned her letters. Except these.|last=Svrluga|first=Susan|date=2015-04-28|work=The Washington Post|access-date=2018-05-01|language=en-US|issn=0190-8286}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/2015/05/03/403946549/martha-washingtons-letters-reveal-a-vital-partner-to-george|title=Martha Washington's Letters Reveal A Vital Partner To George|work=NPR.org|access-date=2018-05-01|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://news.virginia.edu/content/uva-publish-rare-letters-first-lady-martha-washington|title=U.Va. to Publish Rare Letters of First Lady Martha Washington|date=2015-04-29|work=UVA Today|access-date=2018-04-26|language=en}}</ref> and was the co-editor and then editor of ''The Papers of George Washington, Revolutionary War Series'', volumes 3\u20134, 11, 13, 15, 18, and 20.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://gwpapers.virginia.edu/editions/letterpress/revolutionary-war-series/volume-13-december-1777-february-1778/|title=Volume 13: Dec. 1777 \u2013 Feb. 1778 \u2013 The Washington Papers|work=The Washington Papers|access-date=2018-04-26|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016 Lengel left academia and relocated from Charlottesville, VA to Washington, D.C. to take on the role of Chief Historian for the [[White House Historical Association]]. The David M. Rubenstein National Center for White House History is the Association's institute for White House research and education.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.whitehousehistory.org/press-room/press-releases/edward-lengel-named-chief-historian|title=Edward Lengel Named Chief Historian|work=WHHA|access-date=2018-04-26|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, [[Colonial Williamsburg]] announced that Lengel would be their Revolutionary in Residence whereby Lengel will author the historical text of a new edition of \u201cColonial Williamsburg: The Official Guide.\u201d<ref name=\"Edward G. Lengel\"/> The  position allowed Lengel to become an independent historian and full-time author.\n\nLengel has occupied other advisory and board positions including:\n\n* Humanities Advisor, World War I and America, a NEH-funded educational project of the Library of America (wwiamerica.org)\n* Advisory Board, [[United States World War I Centennial Commission|United States World War One Centennial Commission]].\n* Trustee, [[Woodrow Wilson Presidential Library]] Foundation, Staunton, VA, July 2011-July 2013.\n* Service as chair of Library and Archives Committee, and member of Education Committee.\n* Citizen Advisory Council, Virginia Commission on the Centennial of Woodrow Wilson's Presidency, July 2011\u20132012\n* Board of Directors, World War I Memorial Project, July 2011 \u2013 Present<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.edwardlengel.com/wp/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/EDWARDLENGEL_CV2018.pdf|title=Edward Lengel, Professional C.V.|last=Edward|first=Lengel|date=April 26, 2018|website=edwardlengel.com }}</ref>\n\n== Honors and awards ==\nLengel's honors include the [[National Humanities Medal]], received for his work with the Washington Papers Project. He secured the Norman B. Tomlinson, Jr. book prize, and the Rawlings Prize, and he has been recognized by the [[Army Historical Foundation]] and the U.S. Military History Group.\n\n* Outstanding Book Award, Army Historical Foundation for ''Thunder and Flames'', 2015\n* Master Corporal Jan Stanislaw Jakobczak Memorial Book Award, U.S. Military History Group for ''Thunder and Flames'', 2015<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kansaspress.ku.edu/978-0-7006-2084-5.html|title=Thunder and Flames|website=kansaspress.ku.edu|access-date=2018-05-01}}</ref>\n* Outstanding Professor Award, University of Virginia Inter-Sorority Council, 2015\n* George Washington Masonic Memorial Award, for scholarship on George Washington, 2014.\n* Norman B. Tomlinson, Jr., book prize for ''To Conquer Hell: The Meuse-Argonne'', 1918; The Western Front Association, 2008.\n* National Humanities Medal (with Washington Papers Project), 2005\n* General and Mrs. Matthew B. Ridgway Military History Research Grant, U.S. Army Military History Institute, 2003.\n* Rawlings Prize (Albemarle County Historical Society), 1999 and 2001. Governor's Fellowship (University of Virginia), 1995\u20131996.\n* Dumas Malone Traveling Fellowship (University of Virginia), 1994\u20131995.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.edwardlengel.com/wp/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/EDWARDLENGEL_CV2018.pdf|title=Edward G. Lengel professional C.V.|last=Edward|first=Lengel|date=2018|website=edwardlengel.com}}</ref>\n\n==Published works==\n\n*[https://books.google.com/books?id=ViPT_bL7FG0C ''The Irish through British eyes: perceptions of Ireland in the Famine era''], Greenwood, 2002, {{ISBN|978-0-275-97634-7}}\n*[https://books.google.com/books?id=uzAzFPUPazwC ''World War I memories: an annotated bibliography of personal accounts published in English since 1919''], Scarecrow, 2004, {{ISBN|978-0-8108-5008-8}}\n*[https://books.google.com/books?id=B4prSx7i8wMC ''General George Washington: A Military Life''], Random House, 2005, {{ISBN|978-1-4000-6081-8}}  (reprint Random House, Inc., 2008, {{ISBN|978-0-8129-6950-4}})\n*''[https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/1161008.This_Glorious_Struggle This Glorious Struggle: George Washington's Revolutionary War Letters]'', Editor Edward G. Lengel, Smithsonian Books, 2007, {{ISBN|978-0-06-125131-3}}\n*[https://books.google.com/books?id=1pxkmbci77cC ''To Conquer Hell: The Meuse-Argonne, 1918''], Macmillan, 2008, {{ISBN|978-0-8050-7931-9}}   (2nd edition Henry Holt and Co., 2009, {{ISBN|978-0-8050-8915-8}})\n*''[https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/9109649-inventing-george-washington Inventing George Washington: America's Founder, in Myth and Memory]'', Harper, 2011, {{ISBN|978-0-061-66258-4}}\n*''[https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/24693660-first-entrepreneur First Entrepreneur: How George Washington Built His--and the Nation's--Prosperity]'', De Capo Press, 2016, {{ISBN|978-0-306-82347-3}}\n*''[https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/23583665-thunder-and-flames Thunder and Flames: Americans in the Crucible of Combat, 1917-1918]'', University Press of Kansas, 2015, {{ISBN|978-0-7006-2084-5}}\n*''Never in Finer Company: The Men of the Great War's Lost Battalion'', Da Capo Press, 2018, {{ISBN|978-0306825682}}\n\n== Tours and talks ==\nThroughout his career, Lengel has given speeches and presentations<ref name=\":0\" /> related to his research as he believes, \"engaging with and fellow historians is one of the great joys of being an author.\"<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.edwardlengel.com/tours-talks/|title=Tours and Talks|last=Edward|first=Lengel|date=May 1, 2018|website=edwardlengel.com}}</ref> Presentations include those about his published works, such as his February, 2011 talk at Mount Vernon at the David M. Rubenstein Leadership Hall at The Fred W. Smith National Library to discuss his book ''First Entrepreneur: How George Washington Built His--and the Nation's\u2014Prosperity''<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mountvernon.org/library/library-events-programs/ford-evening-book-talks/ford-book-talk-edward-g-lengel/|title=Ford Evening Book Talk: Edward G. Lengel|website=George Washington's Mount Vernon|language=en|access-date=2018-05-01}}</ref>''.'' Or his 2017 talk, \"Testing the American Way of War: Doughboys in Combat, 1917\u20131918\" at the [[George C. Marshall Foundation]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.marshallfoundation.org/blog/marshall-world-wars/|title=Marshall and The World Wars \u2013 George C. Marshall Foundation|date=2017-01-20|work=George C. Marshall Foundation|access-date=2018-05-01|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nHis tagline of being a, \"storyteller hiking through history,\" is supported by curated or customized events and small-group walking tours of historic sites.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nLengel is also on the Historical Advisory Board for the [[United States World War I Centennial Commission]] and he is one of the contributors to their Podcast series WWI Centennial News.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.worldwar1centennial.org/communicate/2015-12-28-18-26-00/weekly-sync-call.html|title=Weekly Podcast \u2013 World War I Centennial|website=www.worldwar1centennial.org|language=en-gb|access-date=2018-05-01}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.paulagordon.com/shows2/lengel/index.html \"Arrogance of War\"], ''The Paula Gordon Show'' \n*[http://www.vahistorical.org/news/lectures_lengel.htm \"Meuse-Argonne, 1918: The Battle That Ended World War I\"], ''Virginia Historical Society''\n*{{C-SPAN|Edward Lengel}}\n*https://www.whitehousehistory.org/staff/edward-lengel\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lengel, Edward G.}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century American historians]]\n[[Category:1968 births]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox writer\n| embed            = \n| honorific_prefix = \n| name             = Edward G. Lengel\n| honorific_suffix = \n| image            = \n| image_size       = \n| image_upright    = \n| alt              = \n| caption          = \n| native_name      = \n| native_name_lang = \n| pseudonym        = \n| birth_name       = \n| birth_date       = {{Birth date and age|1968|08|09}}\n| birth_place      = \n| death_date       = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| death_place      = \n| resting_place    = \n| occupation       = \n| language         = \n| residence        = \n| nationality      = \n| citizenship      = \n| education        = \n| alma_mater       = \n| period           = \n| genre            = military history<br>\n| subject          = <!-- or: | subjects = -->\n| movement         = \n| notableworks     = ''General George Washington: A Military Life''\n| spouse           = <!-- or: | spouses = -->\n| partner          = <!-- or: | partners = -->\n| children         = \n| relatives        = \n| awards           = a co-recipient of the [[National Humanities Medal]] (for his work on the George Washington Papers project)<br>\n| signature        = \n| signature_alt    = \n| years_active     = \n| module           = \n| website          = <!-- {{URL|example.org}} -->\n| portaldisp       = <!-- \"on\", \"yes\", \"true\", etc; or omit -->\n}}\n\n'''Edward \"Ed\" G. Lengel''' (born August 9, 1968) is an [[United States|American]] author and military historian. He is the 2018 Revolutionary in Residence for [[Colonial Williamsburg]].<ref name=\"Edward G. Lengel\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.colonialwilliamsburg.com/learn/revolutionaries-in-residence/ed-lengel|title=Edward G. Lengel|access-date=2018-04-26}}</ref> His previously published books focus on George Washington's life and legacy, and World War I.\n\nHe is a co-recipient of the [[National Humanities Medal]] (for his work on the George Washington Papers project), and his books have been honored with the [[Army Historical Foundation]] Distinguished Book Award, the Norman B. Tomlinson, Jr. prize, and other awards. He is the author of ''General George Washington: A Military Life'',<ref>{{cite news|last=Berthel|first=Ron|title=New books profile first U.S. president -- and first first lady|url=http://helenair.com/lifestyles/article_6f03424b-c6f5-5c6e-9224-7e82a40df028.html|accessdate=3 March 2011|newspaper=[[Independent Record]]|date=16 July 2005}}</ref> which was a finalist for the 2006 [[George Washington Book Prize]], and his 2018 release ''Never in Finer Company: The Men of the Great War\u2019s Lost Battalion''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.edwardlengel.com/portfolio/282/|title=Never in Finer Company: The Men of the Great War's Lost Battalion - Edward Lengel|work=Edward Lengel|access-date=2018-04-26|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n== Personal Background ==\nEdward G. Lengel was born on August 9, 1968 in Washington, D.C. His father Alan was an elementary school teacher; his mother Shelbia (n\u00e9e: Looper) worked for the Department of Health and Human Services. Lengel has one sibling, Eric Lengel.\n\nLengel received a B.A. in history in 1991 from [[George Mason University]] in Fairfax, Virginia. In 1993, he completed an M.A. in history with the [[University of Virginia]], going on to acquire a Ph.D. from the same university in modern European history in 1998. The title of his dissertation was: ''A 'Perverse and Ill-Fated People': British Perceptions of the Irish, 1840-1860''.\n\nLengel describes his work as, \u201ca storyteller, seeking to unfold history\u2019s human core by walking through ancient lands, sites and battlefields in my own hiking boots.\u201d<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.edwardlengel.com/about/|title=About - Edward Lengel|work=Edward Lengel|access-date=2018-04-26|language=en-US}}</ref> Consequently, Lengel conducts and participates in hiking tours, including leading independent tours, and providing annual conference tours with America's History, LLC.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://americashistoryllc.com/2018/loyalists-vs-patriots-the-road-to-victory-from-musgroves-mill-to-cowpens-august-1780-january-1781/|title=Loyalists vs. Patriots: The Road to Victory from  Musgrove\u2019s Mill to Cowpens, August 1780-January 1781 (September 12-15, 2018)|date=2018-03-06|work=americashistoryllc.com|access-date=2018-04-26|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nLengel is engaged to Caitlin Conley, a research historian and cellist originally from Colorado Springs, Colorado. Lengel has two children from a previous marriage.\n\n== Professional Background ==\nWhile working on his B.A., Lengel worked at the [[George Mason University]] Law Library, 1990-1991. Lengel began his professional career at the University of Virginia. From his beginnings as a research assistant in the University of Virginia Library, he rose to become an Assistant Professor and Assistant Editor in 1997 on the George Washington Papers Project.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.linkedin.com/in/edward-lengel-23598097/|title=Edward Lengel, LinkedIn Profile/Resum\u00e9|last=Edward|first=Lengel|date=April 26, 2018|website=linkedin.com/in/edward-lengel-23598097/}}</ref>\n\nFrom 2010\u20132016 he was Professor and Director of the project that he renamed the Washington Papers Project.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://augustafreepress.com/university-of-virginia-to-publish-rare-letters-of-first-lady-martha-washington/|title=University of Virginia to publish rare letters of First Lady Martha Washington|last=AFP|date=2015-05-02|work=Augusta Free Press|access-date=2018-04-26|language=en-US}}</ref> During Lengel's tenure, he oversaw the creation of the Barbados Diary, Martha Washington Papers and Washington Family Papers projects,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/grade-point/wp/2015/04/28/after-george-washington-died-his-wife-burned-her-letters-except-these/|title=After George Washington died, his wife burned her letters. Except these.|last=Svrluga|first=Susan|date=2015-04-28|work=Washington Post|access-date=2018-05-01|language=en-US|issn=0190-8286}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/2015/05/03/403946549/martha-washingtons-letters-reveal-a-vital-partner-to-george|title=Martha Washington's Letters Reveal A Vital Partner To George|work=NPR.org|access-date=2018-05-01|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://news.virginia.edu/content/uva-publish-rare-letters-first-lady-martha-washington|title=U.Va. to Publish Rare Letters of First Lady Martha Washington|date=2015-04-29|work=UVA Today|access-date=2018-04-26|language=en}}</ref> and was the co-editor and then editor of ''The Papers of George Washington, Revolutionary War Series'', volumes 3\u20134, 11, 13, 15, 18, and 20.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://gwpapers.virginia.edu/editions/letterpress/revolutionary-war-series/volume-13-december-1777-february-1778/|title=Volume 13: Dec. 1777 \u2013 Feb. 1778 - The Washington Papers|work=The Washington Papers|access-date=2018-04-26|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016 Lengel left academia and relocated from Charlottesville, VA to Washington, D.C. to take on the role of Chief Historian for the [[White House Historical Association]]. The David M. Rubenstein National Center for White House History is the Association's institute for White House research and education.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.whitehousehistory.org/press-room/press-releases/edward-lengel-named-chief-historian|title=Edward Lengel Named Chief Historian|work=WHHA|access-date=2018-04-26|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, [[Colonial Williamsburg]] announced that Lengel would be their Revolutionary in Residence whereby Lengel will author the historical text of a new edition of \u201cColonial Williamsburg: The Official Guide.\u201d<ref name=\"Edward G. Lengel\"/> The  position allowed Lengel to become an independent historian and full-time author.\n\nLengel has occupied other advisory and board positions including:\n\n* Humanities Advisor, World War I and America, a NEH-funded educational project of the Library of America (wwiamerica.org)\n* Advisory Board, [[United States World War I Centennial Commission|United States World War One Centennial Commission]].\n* Trustee, [[Woodrow Wilson Presidential Library]] Foundation, Staunton, VA, July 2011-July 2013.\n* Service as chair of Library and Archives Committee, and member of Education Committee.\n* Citizen Advisory Council, Virginia Commission on the Centennial of Woodrow Wilson's Presidency, July 2011 \u2013 2012\n* Board of Directors, World War I Memorial Project, July 2011 \u2013 Present<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.edwardlengel.com/wp/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/EDWARDLENGEL_CV2018.pdf|title=Edward Lengel, Professional C.V.|last=Edward|first=Lengel|date=April 26, 2018|website=edwardlengel.com }}</ref>\n\n== Honors & Awards ==\nLengel's honors include the [[National Humanities Medal]], received for his work with the Washington Papers Project. He secured the Norman B. Tomlinson, Jr. book prize, and the Rawlings Prize, and he has been recognized by the [[Army Historical Foundation]] and the U.S. Military History Group.\n\n* Outstanding Book Award, Army Historical Foundation for ''Thunder and Flames'', 2015\n* Master Corporal Jan Stanislaw Jakobczak Memorial Book Award, U.S. Military History Group for ''Thunder and Flames'', 2015<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kansaspress.ku.edu/978-0-7006-2084-5.html|title=Thunder and Flames|website=kansaspress.ku.edu|access-date=2018-05-01}}</ref>\n* Outstanding Professor Award, University of Virginia Inter-Sorority Council, 2015\n* George Washington Masonic Memorial Award, for scholarship on George Washington, 2014.\n* Norman B. Tomlinson, Jr., book prize for ''To Conquer Hell: The Meuse-Argonne'', 1918; The Western Front Association, 2008.\n* National Humanities Medal (with Washington Papers Project), 2005\n* General and Mrs. Matthew B. Ridgway Military History Research Grant, U.S. Army Military History Institute, 2003.\n* Rawlings Prize (Albemarle County Historical Society), 1999 and 2001. Governor's Fellowship (University of Virginia), 1995-1996.\n* Dumas Malone Traveling Fellowship (University of Virginia), 1994-1995.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.edwardlengel.com/wp/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/EDWARDLENGEL_CV2018.pdf|title=Edward G. Lengel professional C.V.|last=Edward|first=Lengel|date=2018|website=edwardlengel.com}}</ref>\n\n==Published Works==\n\n*[https://books.google.com/books?id=ViPT_bL7FG0C ''The Irish through British eyes: perceptions of Ireland in the Famine era''], Greenwood, 2002, {{ISBN|978-0-275-97634-7}}\n*[https://books.google.com/books?id=uzAzFPUPazwC ''World War I memories: an annotated bibliography of personal accounts published in English since 1919''], Scarecrow, 2004, {{ISBN|978-0-8108-5008-8}}\n*[https://books.google.com/books?id=B4prSx7i8wMC ''General George Washington: A Military Life''], Random House, 2005, {{ISBN|978-1-4000-6081-8}}  (reprint Random House, Inc., 2008, {{ISBN|978-0-8129-6950-4}})\n*''[https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/1161008.This_Glorious_Struggle This Glorious Struggle: George Washington's Revolutionary War Letters]'', Editor Edward G. Lengel, Smithsonian Books, 2007, {{ISBN|978-0-06-125131-3}}\n*[https://books.google.com/books?id=1pxkmbci77cC ''To Conquer Hell: The Meuse-Argonne, 1918''], Macmillan, 2008, {{ISBN|978-0-8050-7931-9}}   (2nd edition Henry Holt and Co., 2009, {{ISBN|978-0-8050-8915-8}})\n*''[https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/9109649-inventing-george-washington Inventing George Washington: America's Founder, in Myth and Memory]'', Harper, 2011, {{ISBN|978-0-061-66258-4}}\n*''[https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/24693660-first-entrepreneur First Entrepreneur: How George Washington Built His--and the Nation's--Prosperity]'', De Capo Press, 2016, {{ISBN|978-0-306-82347-3}}\n*''[https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/23583665-thunder-and-flames Thunder and Flames: Americans in the Crucible of Combat, 1917-1918]'', University Press of Kansas, 2015, {{ISBN|978-0-7006-2084-5}}\n*''Never in Finer Company: The Men of the Great War's Lost Battalion'', Da Capo Press, 2018, {{ISBN|978-0306825682}}\n\n== Tours & Talks ==\nThroughout his career, Lengel has given speeches and presentations<ref name=\":0\" /> related to his research as he believes, \"engaging with and fellow historians is one of the great joys of being an author.\"<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.edwardlengel.com/tours-talks/|title=Tours and Talks|last=Edward|first=Lengel|date=May 1, 2018|website=edwardlengel.com}}</ref> Presentations include those about his published works, such as his February, 2011 talk at Mount Vernon at the David M. Rubenstein Leadership Hall at The Fred W. Smith National Library to discuss his book ''First Entrepreneur: How George Washington Built His--and the Nation's\u2014Prosperity''<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mountvernon.org/library/library-events-programs/ford-evening-book-talks/ford-book-talk-edward-g-lengel/|title=Ford Evening Book Talk: Edward G. Lengel|website=George Washington's Mount Vernon|language=en|access-date=2018-05-01}}</ref>''.'' Or his 2017 talk, \"Testing the American Way of War: Doughboys in Combat, 1917-1918\" at the [[George C. Marshall Foundation]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.marshallfoundation.org/blog/marshall-world-wars/|title=Marshall and The World Wars - George C. Marshall Foundation|date=2017-01-20|work=George C. Marshall Foundation|access-date=2018-05-01|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nHis tagline of being a, \"storyteller hiking through history,\" is supported by curated or customized events and small-group walking tours of historic sites.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nLengel is also on the Historical Advisory Board for the [[United States World War I Centennial Commission]] and he is one of the contributors to their Podcast series WWI Centennial News.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.worldwar1centennial.org/communicate/2015-12-28-18-26-00/weekly-sync-call.html|title=Weekly Podcast - World War I Centennial|website=www.worldwar1centennial.org|language=en-gb|access-date=2018-05-01}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.paulagordon.com/shows2/lengel/index.html \"Arrogance of War\"], ''The Paula Gordon Show'' \n*[http://www.vahistorical.org/news/lectures_lengel.htm \"Meuse-Argonne, 1918: The Battle That Ended World War I\"], ''Virginia Historical Society''\n*{{C-SPAN|Edward Lengel}}\n*https://www.whitehousehistory.org/staff/edward-lengel\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lengel, Edward G.}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century American historians]]\n[[Category:1968 births]]\n", "name_user": "Chris the speller", "label": "safe", "comment": "replaced: -  \u2192  \u2013  (5), 1840-1860 \u2192 1840\u20131860 (5), 2011 \u2013 2012 \u2192 2011\u20132012, August 9, 1968 \u2192 August 9, 1968,, =Washington Post \u2192 =The Washington Post,  & Awards \u2192  and awards, Works \u2192 works, etc.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Edward_G._Lengel"}
{"title_page": "Jiuniang", "text_new": "{{more citations needed|date=June 2014}}\n{{Infobox food\n| name             = Jiuniang\n| image            = Kueh hrua lau cau.jpg\n| image_size       = 250px\n| caption          = A bowl of ''guihua jiuniang'' (\u6842\u82b1\u9152\u917f)\n| alternate_name   = \n| country          = [[China]]\n| region           = [[East Asia]]\n| creator          = \n| course           = \n| type             = [[Rice pudding]]\n| served           = \n| main_ingredient  = [[Glutinous rice]], [[fermentation starter]] ([[yeast]] and ''[[Aspergillus oryzae]]'')\n| variations       = \n| calories         = \n| other            = \n}}\n\n{{Chinese|t=[[wikt:\u9152\u91c0|\u9152\u91c0]]|showflag=p|p=ji\u01d4ni\u00e0ng|j=zau2 yeung6|wuu=ciu nyang|c=|s=|mi=|ci=|altname=|l=Wine brew}}\n'''''Jiuniang''''' (\u9152\u917f, also called '''''l\u00e1oz\u0101o''''' \u91aa\u7cdf, '''''ji\u0101ngm\u01d0ji\u01d4''''' \u6c5f\u7c73\u9152, or '''''ti\u00e1nb\u00e1iji\u01d4''''' \u751c\u767d\u9152 in [[Yunnan]]) is a sweet, soup- or [[Rice pudding|pudding]]-like dish in [[Chinese cuisine]]. It also known as sweet wine or sweet rice wine.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thebeijinger.com/blog/2010/10/31/baiju-and-huangjiu-and-mijiu-oh-my|title=Baiju and Huangjiu and Mijiu, Oh My!|last=lauren_mccarthy|date=2010-10-31|website=www.thebeijinger.com|language=EN|access-date=2019-05-01}}</ref> It consists of a mixture of partially digested rice grains floating in a sweet saccharified liquid, with small amounts of alcohol (1.5\u20132%) and lactic acid (0.5%). It is made by fermenting [[glutinous rice]] with a [[Fermentation starter|starter]] called [[Jiuqu]] (\u9152\u9eb4) containing ''Rhizopus oryzae'' and/or ''Aspergillus oryzae'' and often [[yeast]] and bacteria. \n[[File:Angel Brand Jiuqu (Rice Leuven).jpg|thumb|Jiuqu (Chinese Fermentation Starter)]]\n\nIt was first developed as a [[by-product]] of ''[[mijiu]]'' production and generally speaking is partially digested and fermented rice from a young rice wine (or vinegar) ferment. If eaten quickly or held at 10 degrees or less which halts the fermentation, the product can be consumed as Jiuniang. If the temperatures are raised and fermentation continues, Jiuniang will eventually produce rice wine or rice vinegar. Jiuniang is most commonly made and consumed in the winter, where fermentation can be halted easily.<ref>Li, Jian-rong, and Yun-Hwa P. Hsieh. \"Traditional Chinese food technology and cuisine.\" Asia Pacific journal of clinical nutrition 13.2 (2004).</ref>\n\nOften jiuniang is translated to rice sauce or even rice wine (due to its alcohol content) by western Chinese retailers. It is often made with [[sweet osmanthus]] flowers and the dish is called ''guihua jiuniang'' (\u6842\u82b1\u9152\u917f).\n\n==Service==\n''Jiuniang'' is often served together with small unfilled ''[[tangyuan (food)|tangyuan]]'' during the [[Dongzhi Festival]], a Chinese winter holiday dedicated to the ancestors. When served in such a manner it is called ''jiuniang tangyuan'' (\u9152\u917f\u6c64\u5706) or \"jiuniang yuanzi\" (\u9152\u917f\u5706\u5b50), or  white wine soup bubble ''baijiu tangyuan'' (\u767d\u9152\u6c64\u5706) in Yunnan, or, with Sweet Osmanthus, ''guihua jiuniang tangyuan'' (\u6842\u82b1\u9152\u917f\u6c64\u5706). All forms of ''jiuniang'' are typically eaten with a spoon.\n\n==Similar dishes==\nIt is very similar to the southern Vietnamese dish ''[[c\u01a1m r\u01b0\u1ee3u]]'', which usually contains balls of rice. It is also similar to the Korean ''[[sikhye]]'' and Japanese ''[[amazake]]'', although these are a bit thinner in texture and considered drinks rather than soups or puddings.\n[[File:Ciux jak.PNG|thumb|[[Fermentation starter]], known as jiuqu (\u9152\u85e5) used to make jiuniang]]\n\n==See also==\n*[[Rice pudding]]\n*[[Mijiu]]\n*[[Tapai]]\n*[[Amazake]] - a Japanese equivalent\n*[[Sikhye]] - a Korean equivalent\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* History of the later Han * Volume 32:  \u300a\u540e\u6c49\u4e66\u3002\u6a0a\u4f20\u300b\uff1a\u201c\u53c8\u91ce\u738b\u5c81\u732e\u7518\u91aa\u818f\u9967\u3002\u201d\u674e\u8d24\u6ce8\uff1a\u201c\u91aa\uff0c\u9187\u9152\u6c41\u6ed3\u76f8\u5c06\u4e5f\u3002\u201d\u5f15\u4f38\u4e3a\u6d4a\u9152\u3002\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20100122145410/http://www.cultural-china.com/chinaWH/html/en/8Kaleidoscope1012.html ''Jiuniang'' page]\n\n{{Rice pudding}}\n{{Rice drinks}}\n\n[[Category:Chinese alcoholic drinks]]\n[[Category:Chinese desserts]]\n[[Category:Chinese soups]]\n[[Category:Rice pudding]]\n[[Category:Rice wine]]\n\n\n{{China-cuisine-stub}}\n{{Drink-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox prepared food\n| name             = Jiuniang\n| image            = Kueh hrua lau cau.jpg\n| image_size       = 250px\n| caption          = A bowl of ''guihua jiuniang'' (\u6842\u82b1\u9152\u917f)\n| alternate_name   = \n| country          = [[China]]\n| region           = [[East Asia]]\n| creator          = \n| course           = \n| type             = [[Rice pudding]]\n| served           = \n| main_ingredient  = [[Glutinous rice]], [[fermentation starter]] ([[yeast]] and ''[[Aspergillus oryzae]]'')\n| variations       = \n| calories         = \n| other            = \n}}\n{{more citations needed|date=June 2014}}\n{{Chinese|t=[[wikt:\u9152\u91c0|\u9152\u91c0]]|showflag=p|p=ji\u01d4ni\u00e0ng|j=zau2 yeung6|wuu=ciu nyang|c=|s=|mi=|ci=|altname=|l=Wine brew}}\n'''''Jiuniang''''' (\u9152\u917f, also called '''''l\u00e1oz\u0101o''''' \u91aa\u7cdf, '''''ji\u0101ngm\u01d0ji\u01d4''''' \u6c5f\u7c73\u9152, or '''''ti\u00e1nb\u00e1iji\u01d4''''' \u751c\u767d\u9152 in [[Yunnan]]) is a sweet, soup- or [[Rice pudding|pudding]]-like dish in [[Chinese cuisine]]. It also known as sweet wine or sweet rice wine.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thebeijinger.com/blog/2010/10/31/baiju-and-huangjiu-and-mijiu-oh-my|title=Baiju and Huangjiu and Mijiu, Oh My!|last=lauren_mccarthy|date=2010-10-31|website=www.thebeijinger.com|language=EN|access-date=2019-05-01}}</ref> It consists of a mixture of partially digested rice grains floating in a sweet saccharified liquid, with small amounts of alcohol (1.5\u20132%) and lactic acid (0.5%). It is made by fermenting [[glutinous rice]] with a [[Fermentation starter|starter]] called [[Jiuqu]] (\u9152\u9eb4) containing ''Rhizopus oryzae'' and/or ''Aspergillus oryzae'' and often [[yeast]] and bacteria. \n[[File:Angel Brand Jiuqu (Rice Leuven).jpg|thumb|Jiuqu (Chinese Fermentation Starter)]]\n\nIt was first developed as a [[by-product]] of ''[[mijiu]]'' production and generally speaking is partially digested and fermented rice from a young rice wine (or vinegar) ferment. If eaten quickly or held at 10 degrees or less which halts the fermentation, the product can be consumed as Jiuniang. If the temperatures are raised and fermentation continues, Jiuniang will eventually produce rice wine or rice vinegar. Jiuniang is most commonly made and consumed in the winter, where fermentation can be halted easily.<ref>Li, Jian-rong, and Yun-Hwa P. Hsieh. \"Traditional Chinese food technology and cuisine.\" Asia Pacific journal of clinical nutrition 13.2 (2004).</ref>\n\nOften jiuniang is translated to rice sauce or even rice wine (due to its alcohol content) by western Chinese retailers. It is often made with [[sweet osmanthus]] flowers and the dish is called ''guihua jiuniang'' (\u6842\u82b1\u9152\u917f).\n\n==Service==\n''Jiuniang'' is often served together with small unfilled ''[[tangyuan (food)|tangyuan]]'' during the [[Dongzhi Festival]], a Chinese winter holiday dedicated to the ancestors. When served in such a manner it is called ''jiuniang tangyuan'' (\u9152\u917f\u6c64\u5706) or \"jiuniang yuanzi\" (\u9152\u917f\u5706\u5b50) \uff0cor  white wine soup bubble ''baijiu tangyuan'' (\u767d\u9152\u6c64\u5706) in Yunnan, or, with Sweet Osmanthus, ''guihua jiuniang tangyuan'' (\u6842\u82b1\u9152\u917f\u6c64\u5706). All forms of ''jiuniang'' are typically eaten with a spoon.\n\n==Similar dishes==\nIt is very similar to the southern Vietnamese dish ''[[c\u01a1m r\u01b0\u1ee3u]]'', which usually contains balls of rice. It is also similar to the Korean ''[[sikhye]]'' and Japanese ''[[amazake]]'', although these are a bit thinner in texture and considered drinks rather than soups or puddings.\n[[File:Ciux jak.PNG|thumb|[[Fermentation starter]], known as jiuqu (\u9152\u85e5) used to make jiuniang]]\n\n==See also==\n*[[Rice pudding]]\n*[[Mijiu]]\n*[[Tapai]]\n*[[Amazake]] - a Japanese equivalent\n*[[Sikhye]] - a Korean equivalent\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* History of the later Han * Volume 32:  \u300a\u540e\u6c49\u4e66\u3002\u6a0a\u4f20\u300b\uff1a\u201c\u53c8\u91ce\u738b\u5c81\u732e\u7518\u91aa\u818f\u9967\u3002\u201d\u674e\u8d24\u6ce8\uff1a\u201c\u91aa\uff0c\u9187\u9152\u6c41\u6ed3\u76f8\u5c06\u4e5f\u3002\u201d\u5f15\u4f38\u4e3a\u6d4a\u9152\u3002\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20100122145410/http://www.cultural-china.com/chinaWH/html/en/8Kaleidoscope1012.html ''Jiuniang'' page]\n\n{{Rice pudding}}\n{{Rice drinks}}\n{{China-cuisine-stub}}\n{{Drink-stub}}\n\n[[Category:Chinese alcoholic drinks]]\n[[Category:Chinese desserts]]\n[[Category:Chinese soups]]\n[[Category:Rice pudding]]\n[[Category:Rice wine]]\n", "name_user": "Danielt998", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jiuniang"}
