{"title_page": "David Weir (Scottish footballer)", "text_new": "{{Other people|David Weir}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2013}}\n{{infobox football biography\n| name            = David Weir\n| image           = David Weir 2014.jpg\n| caption         = Weir as [[Brentford F.C.|Brentford]] assistant in 2014\n| fullname        = David Gillespie Weir<ref name=\"Hugman2007\u201308 427\">{{Cite book\n | editor-first = Barry J.\n | editor-last = Hugman\n | title = The PFA Footballers' Who's Who 2007\u201308\n | year = 2007\n | publisher = Mainstream Publishing\n | isbn = 978-1-84596-246-3\n | page = 427 }}</ref>\n| birth_date      = {{Birth date and age|1970|5|10|df=y}}\n| birth_place     = [[Falkirk]], Scotland\n| height          = {{height|ft=6|in=3}}\n| currentclub     = \n| position        = [[Centre back]]\n| collegeyears1     = 1988\u20131992 | college1 = [[Evansville Purple Aces men's soccer|Evansville Purple Aces]]<ref name=\"Weir in US\"/>\n| years1          = 1992\u20131996 | clubs1 = [[Falkirk F.C.|Falkirk]]                         | caps1 = 133 | goals1 = 8\n| years2          = 1996\u20131999 | clubs2 = [[Heart of Midlothian F.C.|Heart of Midlothian]] | caps2 = 76  | goals2 = 6\n| years3          = 1999\u20132007 | clubs3 = [[Everton F.C.|Everton]]                         | caps3 = 235 | goals3 = 10\n| years4          = 2007\u20132012 | clubs4 = [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]]                         | caps4 = 162 | goals4 = 4\n| totalcaps       = 606 | totalgoals = 28\n| nationalyears1  = 1997\u20132010\n| nationalteam1 = [[Scotland national football team|Scotland]]\n| nationalcaps1  = 69\n| nationalgoals1 = 1\n| manageryears1   = 2013      | managerclubs1 = [[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]] \n}}\n'''David Gillespie Weir''' (born 10 May 1970) is a Scottish [[association football|football]] player and coach.\n\nBorn in [[Falkirk]], Weir played as a [[Defender (association football)|defender]], and began his professional career with his home-town club, [[Falkirk F.C.|Falkirk]], after having attended the [[University of Evansville]] in the United States. After four seasons with the Bairns, Weir then moved on to [[Heart of Midlothian F.C.|Heart of Midlothian]] where he won the [[1998 Scottish Cup Final|1998 Scottish Cup]]. He joined [[Everton F.C.|Everton]] in 1999 and spent seven years with the club, becoming club captain under two different managers. Weir then moved to Rangers in 2007 and became club captain after [[Barry Ferguson]] was stripped of the role in April 2009. Weir called time on his playing career in May 2012.\n\nWeir won his first [[cap (sport)|cap]] for the [[Scotland national football team]] in 1997 and was selected for their [[1998 FIFA World Cup]] squad. He retired from international football in 2002, when [[Berti Vogts]] was the manager, but returned when [[Walter Smith]] took charge in 2004. Weir became the oldest Scotland player when he played in [[UEFA Euro 2012 qualifying]] matches in 2010. He finished his international career with  69 [[Cap (sport)|caps]], which makes him  [[Scotland national football team records#Most capped players|Scotland's seventh-most capped player]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scottishfa.co.uk/scottish_football_players.cfm?page=138|title=International Roll of Honour|publisher=Scottish Football Association|accessdate=17 June 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101011104402/http://www.scottishfa.co.uk/scottish_football_players.cfm?page=138|archive-date=11 October 2010|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nWeir had a brief spell as manager of [[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]] in 2013. He has since assisted [[Mark Warburton]] at [[Brentford F.C.|Brentford]], [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]] and [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]].\n\n==Playing career==\n===Club===\n====Evansville Purple Aces====\nWeir was scouted by the [[University of Evansville]] during a schools festival in [[Grantham, Lincolnshire]]. He moved to the United States on a [[Sports scholarships|scholarship]] from 1988 to 1991.<ref name=\"Weir in US\" /> Whilst in [[Evansville, Indiana|Evansville]], he was converted from a centre back to a striker due to his lack of pace.<ref name=\"Weir in US\" /> Weir excelled in this position, scoring 28 goals in 27 matches during his [[Senior (education)|senior]] year. This form led to him being named an [[Division I First-Team All-American (soccer)|NCAA All-American]] and [[Midwest Collegiate Conference|Midwest Collegiate Conference Player of the Year]] in 1990.<ref name=\"Weir in US\">{{cite news\n| title = How Davie Weir wowed the Yanks\n| url = http://www.newsoftheworld.co.uk/scottish/scottish_sport/772766/Fred-Schmalz-reveals-Gers-ace-was-too-slow-to-be-a-defender.html\n| work = News of the World\n| date = 4 April 2010}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gopurpleaces.com/news/2014/4/21/MSOC_0421142355.aspx|title=Former UE Soccer Standout Weir Helps Brentford to Promotion|publisher=}}</ref> Weir is tied for the school record with 50 career goals and ranks second in school history with 129 career points.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n====Falkirk====\nUpon returning from the United States Weir trained with [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]]; however, he did not sign a professional contract. In 1992, he joined then [[Scottish Football League First Division|Scottish First Division]] side [[Falkirk F.C.|Falkirk]] and went on to make 134 appearances for the club and score eight goals. He was part of the side which won promotion to the Scottish Premier Division. Weir also won the [[1993 Scottish Challenge Cup Final|1993 Scottish Challenge Cup]] on 12 December, playing in the side that defeated [[St Mirren F.C.|St Mirren]] 3\u20130 at [[Fir Park]] in [[Motherwell]].<ref>{{Cite news |first=David |last=McKinney |title=Football: Falkirk find their fire |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football-falkirk-find-their-fire-1467272.html |work=The Independent |location=London |date=13 December 1993 |accessdate=21 March 2015  }}</ref>\n\n====Heart of Midlothian====\nOn 30 June 1996, Weir moved to Premier Division side [[Heart of Midlothian F.C.|Heart of Midlothian]]. He made his debut for the club in a [[Scottish League Cup|League Cup]] match against [[Stenhousemuir F.C.|Stenhousemuir]] on 14 August 1996 and scored his first goal three days later. Weir netted Hearts second goal in a 3\u20132 win over [[Kilmarnock F.C.|Kilmarnock]]. His first sending off was in an infamous game against [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]] at [[Ibrox Stadium|Ibrox]] on 14 September 1996. Rangers won the match 3\u20130 but Hearts had four players ordered off in a twenty-minute spell.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.soccerbase.com/results3.sd?gameid=241789 | title=Rangers 3 (1) \u2013 0 (0) Hearts| work=Soccerbase | accessdate= 14 September 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/hearts-face-inquiry-into-ibrox-fracas-1363509.html | title=Hearts face inquiry into Ibrox fracas | work=The Independent | accessdate=16 September 2010 | location=London | first=David | last=McKinney | date=16 September 1996}}</ref>\n\nWeir won his second career honour, the [[1998 Scottish Cup Final|1998 Scottish Cup]], by beating Rangers 2\u20131 in the final at [[Celtic Park]]. He left [[Tynecastle Stadium|Tynecastle]] midway through the following season when he was purchased by Everton for \u00a3250,000. Weir played 116 games in all for Hearts and scored twelve goals.\n\n====Everton====\nWeir joined [[Everton F.C.|Everton]] on 16 February 1999 and made his debut in a league match against [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]] the next day as Everton won, 5\u20130, coming on as a substitute for [[John Oster]] after 73 minutes.<ref>{{Cite news | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/sport/football/scottish_league/280417.stm | title=Weir flies south | publisher=BBC Sport | date=16 February 1999}}</ref> Weir's first goal for Everton was a last-minute equaliser against [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]] in a 4\u20134 draw in October 1998. At the end of the 2001\u201302 season, Weir was voted Everton's Player of the Year by planetfootball's readers, with Weir the only player to reach four figures in terms of votes.<ref>{{cite news|title=King David|url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11671/2237033/|publisher=Sky Sports|date=10 May 2002|accessdate=5 June 2013}}</ref> In the [[Merseyside derby]] match on 19 April 2003, Weir received his first red card for the club as Everton lost 2\u20131 and played with 9 men after [[Gary Naysmith]] was also sent off.\n\nHe had a very successful time with the Merseyside club, playing regularly for eight years, making 269 appearances (scoring 10 goals in the process), playing in European competition, becoming club captain under two different managers \u2013 [[Walter Smith]] and [[David Moyes]] \u2013 and winning the bulk of his Scotland caps on the strength of his performances for the Toffees. During the 2005\u201306 season, his side played in [[2005\u201306 UEFA Champions League|UEFA Champions League]] but lost 4\u20132 on aggregate to Spanish side [[Villarreal CF]] in the third qualifying round. After being eliminated in the Champions League, Everton played in the [[2005\u201306 UEFA Cup|UEFA Cup]] but lost again, this time to Romanian side [[FC Dinamo Bucure\u0219ti|Dinamo Bucure\u0219ti]] 5\u20132 on aggregate in the first round of UEFA Cup.\n\n====Rangers====\nOn 16 January 2007, Weir signed for Rangers on an initial six-month deal after Everton released him from his contract early. He teamed up again with former manager Walter Smith.<ref name=\"Weir completes switch to Rangers\">{{cite news\n| title = Weir completes switch to Rangers\n| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/r/rangers/6262693.stm\n| publisher=BBC Sport \n| date = 16 January 2007}}</ref> He made his Rangers debut against [[Dunfermline Athletic F.C.|Dunfermline Athletic]] on 21 January 2007.<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Dunfermline 0\u20131 Rangers\n| url = http://newsimg.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/scot_prem/6277399.stm\n| publisher=BBC Sport \n| first=Thomas |last=McGuigan\n| date = 21 January 2007}}</ref>\nHis performances for the Glasgow club were enough to secure a one-year contract. After his man-of-the-match performance against [[St Mirren F.C.|St Mirren]] on 8 April 2007, he revealed that he may remain at [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]] for the [[2007\u201308 in Scottish football|2007\u201308 season]] after discussing the issue with his family. His agent met with Rangers on 19 April to discuss a possible extension to his contract, which was due to expire at the end of that season. Weir signed a one-year extension to his deal, keeping him at Rangers until the summer of 2008.<ref>{{cite news\n|title = Weir signs one-year deal at Ibrox|url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/r/rangers/6562919.stm|publisher=BBC Sport |date = 20 April 2007}}</ref>\n\nHe scored his first Rangers goal against [[FK Zeta]] in a [[UEFA Champions League]] qualifier, on 31 July 2007.<ref name=\"Rangers 2-0 FK Zeta\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/europe/6922795.stm|publisher=BBC Sport|title=Rangers 2\u20130 FK Zeta |date=31 July 2007|first=Colin|last=Moffat}}</ref> Weir was highly praised for his endurance during the 2007\u201308 season as Rangers chased [[The Quadruple]]. Despite being in his late 30s, he managed sixty appearances that season and produced some outstanding performances alongside [[Carlos Cu\u00e9llar]] in the centre of defence. Weir won his third and fourth trophies of his career in 2008, as Rangers claimed [[Scottish Cup]] and [[Scottish League Cup|League Cup]] glory. On 3 July he signed a further one-year contract extension to his deal.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/r/rangers/7487125.stm|title=Veteran duo seal new Ibrox deals|date=3 July 2008|publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref> He was appointed Rangers' captain on 3 April 2009 after [[Barry Ferguson]] had been stripped the role following an incident whilst on international duty. Weir won the [[2008\u201309 Scottish Premier League|League]] and [[Scottish Cup|Cup]] double in season [[2008\u201309 Rangers F.C. season|2008\u201309]] with Rangers and signed a further one-year contract extension which saw playing into his forties.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/r/rangers/8077300.stm|title=Weir poised for new Rangers deal |date=1 June 2009|publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/r/rangers/8134602.stm|title=Weir not pondering his retirement|date=4 July 2009|publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref> In March 2010, Weir won the [[Scottish Premier League monthly awards|Player of the month award]] for February<ref name=\"Weir feb\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/r/rangers/8555925.stm|title=Rangers' Weir wins February award|date=8 March 2010|publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref> and followed this up with the Clydesdale Bank Premier League Player of the Year award for the 2009\u201310 season.<ref name=\"Weir wins Clydesdale award\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/scot_prem/8630065.stm|title=Rangers duo win Clydesdale manager and player awards |date=19 April 2010|publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref> On 7 May 2010 it was announced Weir had also won the [[SFWA Footballer of the Year|Scottish Football Writers' Association Footballer of the Year Award]], the oldest player ever to receive this accolade \u2013 just three days before his 40th birthday.<ref name=\"Weir wins writers' award\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/r/rangers/8667560.stm|title=Rangers captain David Weir wins writers' award|date=7 May 2010|publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref> Soon afterwards, Weir agreed another one-year contract which saw him play on into his forties.<ref>{{Cite news | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/r/rangers/8777141.stm | title=David Weir agrees new Rangers contract  | date=30 June 2010 | accessdate=22 September 2011 | publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref> He became the third oldest player ever to compete in the [[UEFA Champions League]] on 14 September 2010 in Rangers' 0-0 away draw with [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] at [[Old Trafford]] and he became the joint oldest outfield player in Champions League history when he played against Bursaspor in December 2010, aged 40 years 211 days.<ref>{{cite news|last=Pattullo |first=Alan |url=http://sport.scotsman.com/sport/David-Weir-joins--.6651998.jp|title=David Weir joins lofty company as oldest player to grace Champions League |work=The Scotsman|date=7 December 2010 |accessdate=22 February 2011}}</ref> Weir captured his third league title with Rangers as captain on the week of his 41st birthday when Rangers defeated Kilmarnock 5-1 on the last day of the season beating Celtic to the title by a single point.\n\nOn 26 May 2011, it was announced that Weir was to be inducted into the [[Rangers F.C. Hall of Fame]]. He has become the first ever player to be inducted into the Hall of Fame whilst under contract at the club.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportinglife.com/football/scottishpremier/news/story_get.cgi?STORY_NAME=soccer/11/05/26/SOCCER_Rangers_Weir.html&TEAMHD=scotspremiership&BID=425 |title=Weir Revels in Hall of Fame Honour |work=Sporting Life |accessdate=31 August 2011 }}{{dead link|date=December 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> On 17 July 2011, Weir signed a new one-year deal with Rangers.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/14177444.stm?|title=Rangers captain David Weir signs one-year deal at Ibrox |publisher=BBC Sport|date=17 July 2011 | accessdate=11 August 2011 }}</ref> Following Walter Smith's retirement as manager, [[Ally McCoist]] succeeded him. Under McCoist, Weir did not play in the League, and he was replaced as captain by [[Steven Davis]]. Weir made his last appearance in the Champions' League Third qualifying round 1st leg against Swedish side [[Malm\u00f6 FF]]. Weir played for 29 minutes, before being replaced by [[Juan Manuel Ortiz]].\n\nOn 17 January 2012, he announced that he would be leaving Rangers in order to continue his career at an unnamed club in England. The club he was close to signing for was [[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]] and he trained with the Blades for several weeks, however he moved into coaching instead.<ref name=\"Weir poised for job\">{{cite news|title=David Weir poised for job as Sheffield United boss|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/22833212|accessdate=10 June 2013|publisher=BBC Sport|date=9 June 2013}}</ref>\n\n=== International ===\nWeir earned his first [[cap (football)|cap]] for [[Scotland national football team|Scotland]] in a 1\u20130 defeat to [[Wales national football team|Wales]] on 27 May 1997.<ref name=\"Scotland v Wales\">{{cite news\n |title        = Scotland v Wales\n |url          = http://www.scottishfa.co.uk/match_details.cfm?matchid=57898\n |publisher    = Scottish FA\n |date         = 14 November 2007\n |access-date  = 14 November 2007\n |archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20071204072528/http://www.scottishfa.co.uk/match_details.cfm?matchid=57898\n |archive-date = 4 December 2007\n |url-status     = dead\n |df           = dmy-all\n}}</ref> He scored his one and only goal for Scotland in [[FIFA World Cup qualification|a World Cup qualifier]] against [[Latvia national football team|Latvia]] at [[Hampden Park]] on 6 October 2001.<ref name=\"Scotland v Latvia\">{{cite news\n| title = Scots out with a whimper\n| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/world_cup_2002/1576720.stm\n| publisher = BBC Sport\n| accessdate = 21 September 2011\n| date = 6 October 2001}}</ref>\n\nWeir temporarily retired from international football in 2002 after his performance in a [[UEFA Euro 2004 qualifying]] match against the [[Faroe Islands national football team|Faroe Islands]] was criticised by manager [[Berti Vogts]].<ref>{{Cite news | url=http://newsvote.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/internationals/scotland/2232138.stm?dynamic_vote=ON#vote_vogts_07_09_2002 | title=Lucky Scots scrape draw in Faroes| publisher=BBC Sport | date=7 September 2002}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news | url=http://sport.scotsman.com/football/Weir-I-was-right-to.2381553.jp | title=Weir: I was right to quit Scotland | work=The Scotsman | date=27 November 2002}}</ref> He returned to international football when Walter Smith was appointed Scotland manager in December 2004.\n\nWeir became a member of the [[Scotland national football team roll of honour]] when he won his 50th Scotland cap. This milestone came in a match against [[Lithuania national football team|Lithuania]] on 6 September 2006, in which he captained his country to a 2\u20131 win.<ref name=\"Lithuania v Scotland\">{{cite news\n |title        = Lithuania v Scotland\n |url          = http://www.scottishfa.co.uk/match_details.cfm?matchid=58167\n |publisher    = Scottish FA\n |date         = 14 November 2007\n |access-date  = 21 January 2012\n |archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20071204072532/http://www.scottishfa.co.uk/match_details.cfm?matchid=58167\n |archive-date = 4 December 2007\n |url-status     = dead\n |df           = dmy-all\n}}</ref> He  captained Scotland four times.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scottishfa.co.uk/international_fixture_details.cfm?page=32&matchID=58167|title=Lithuania vs Scotland Match Report|publisher=Scottish FA|accessdate=31 August 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scottishfa.co.uk/international_fixture_details.cfm?page=32&matchID=62498|title=Scotland vs Faroe Islands Match Report|publisher=Scottish FA|accessdate=31 August 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scottishfa.co.uk/international_fixture_details.cfm?page=32&matchID=55680|title=Japan vs Scotland Match Report|publisher=Scottish FA|accessdate=31 August 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scottishfa.co.uk/international_fixture_details.cfm?page=32&matchID=55681|title=Bulgaria vs Scotland Match Report|publisher=Scottish FA|accessdate=31 August 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 August 2010, Weir was recalled to the Scotland squad at the age of 40 for the [[UEFA Euro 2012 qualifying|Euro 2012]] qualifying matches against [[Lithuania national football team|Lithuania]] and [[Liechtenstein national football team|Liechtenstein]] in September 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/news/story?id=817106&sec=euro2012&cc=5739|title=Scotland recall for 40-year-old Weir|date=24 August 2010|work=ESPN Soccernet}}</ref> Weir became the oldest ever Scottish football international when he played against Lithuania on 3 September 2010, aged 40 years and 116 days, breaking [[Jim Leighton]]'s previous record of 40 years and 78 days.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/scotland/8955170.stm |title=David Weir set for Scotland milestone |date=3 September 2010|publisher = BBC Sport}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/match/3118708 |title=Lithuania v Scotland Match facts |date=3 September 2010 |work=The Guardian |location=London}}</ref><ref name=rsssoldyoung>[http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/oldest-youngest.html Oldest and Youngest Players and Goal-scorers in International Football], [[RSSSF]], 20 September 2018</ref>\n\n==Coaching and management==\n\n===Everton coach===\nIn February 2012, Weir returned to Everton in a coaching capacity with the club's academy and reserve teams. He made his reserve-team debut for the club against [[Liverpool F.C. Reserves and Academy|Liverpool]] on the day of his return.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.evertonfc.com/news/archive/2012/02/21/weir-back-with-blues|title=Weir Back With Blues|publisher=Everton F.C.|accessdate=21 February 2012|date=21 February 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120326054517/http://www.evertonfc.com/news/archive/2012/02/21/weir-back-with-blues|archive-date=26 March 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> When manager [[David Moyes]] left the club to replace [[Alex Ferguson|Sir Alex Ferguson]] at Manchester United in May 2013, Weir was interviewed by [[Bill Kenwright]] for the vacant role at Everton, but the job instead went to [[Roberto Mart\u00ednez]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2013/may/30/roberto-martinez-everton-second-interview|title=Roberto Mart\u00ednez set for second interview for Everton manager's job|work=The Guardian|accessdate=5 June 2013|date=5 June 2013|location=London|first=Andy|last=Hunter}}</ref>\n\n===Sheffield United manager===\nIn June 2013, Weir signed a three-year deal to manage [[Football League One|League One]] side [[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]].<ref name=\"Blades appoint Weir\">{{cite news|title=David Weir: Sheffield United appoint Everton coach as boss|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/22843168|accessdate=10 June 2013|publisher=BBC Sport|date=10 June 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"guardian appointment\">{{cite news|title=David Weir is appointed new Sheffield United manager on three-year deal|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2013/jun/10/sheffield-united-david-weir|accessdate=10 June 2013|work=The Guardian|date=10 June 2013|location=London}}</ref>  Despite winning his first competitive game in charge, a 2\u20131 victory over [[Notts County F.C.|Notts County]], United struggled under his management and failed to win any of their following twelve matches, leading to growing pressure from the club's fans for Weir to be sacked.<ref name=\"enjoying bdtbl\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thestar.co.uk/sport/sheffield-united/sheffield-united-why-weir-is-still-loving-life-at-the-lane-1-6093667|title=Why Weir is still loving life at the Lane|work=The Sheffield Star|accessdate=29 September 2013|date=28 September 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131001133534/http://www.thestar.co.uk/sport/sheffield-united/sheffield-united-why-weir-is-still-loving-life-at-the-lane-1-6093667|archive-date=1 October 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref>  After United were beaten at home by [[Football League Two|League Two]] side [[Hartlepool United F.C.|Hartlepool United]], eliminating them from the [[Football League Trophy]], Weir was sacked on 11 October 2013.<ref name=\"blades exit\">{{cite web|url=http://www.sufc.co.uk/news/article/20131011-weir-departs-1110494.aspx|title=Manager Weir departs as Blades Boss|publisher=Sheffield United F.C.|date=11 October 2013|accessdate=11 October 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Assistant to Mark Warburton===\nFollowing the departure of caretaker [[Alan Kernaghan]], Weir was appointed as [[Mark Warburton]]'s assistant manager at League One side [[Brentford F.C.|Brentford]] on 16 December 2013.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/25400456 |title=Brentford: David Weir joins as Kernaghan and Farrell leave |publisher=BBC Sport |date=16 December 2013 |accessdate=16 December 2013}}</ref> After a successful season which saw Brentford promoted to the [[Football League Championship|Championship]], Weir signed a new one-year rolling contract to remain with the [[Griffin Park]] club.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.getwestlondon.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/brentford-manager-agrees-new-contract-7331786|title=Brentford manager agrees new contract|first=Jacob|last=Murtagh|date=26 June 2014|publisher=}}</ref> On 17 February 2015, it was announced that Weir, Warburton and Sporting Director Frank McParland would leave Brentford at the end of the [[2014\u201315 Brentford F.C. season|2014\u201315]] season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.brentfordfc.co.uk/news/article/brentford-fc-mark-warburton-frank-mcparland-david-weir-statement-2277027.aspx|title=Brentford FC club statement 17.02.2015|work= |publisher=Brentford FC}}</ref>\n\nOn 15 June 2015, Weir returned to Rangers on a three-year deal to assist Warburton.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rangers.co.uk/news/headlines/item/9468-warburton-appointed-manager |title=Warburton Appointed Manager |work=Rangers |publisher=rangers.co.uk |date=15 June 2015 |accessdate=15 June 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150618003515/http://www.rangers.co.uk/news/headlines/item/9468-warburton-appointed-manager |archivedate=18 June 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Weir and Warburton extended their contracts with Rangers by a further year in July 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|title =Rangers: Mark Warburton completes contract extension |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/36770547 |publisher=BBC Sport|date=12 July 2016|accessdate=18 November 2016}}</ref> In February 2017 Rangers released an official statement claiming that Weir, Warburton and head of recruitment Frank McParland had resigned their positions, effective immediately.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://rangers.co.uk/news/headlines/club-statement-74/ |title=Club Statement |work= |publisher=Rangers F.C. |date=10 February 2017 |accessdate=10 February 2017}}</ref> This was denied in a joint statement by all three men, but their tenure at the club had nonetheless come to an end.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/sport/soccer/mark-warburton-reiterates-he-did-not-resign-from-rangers-job-1.2976472|title=Mark Warburton reiterates he did not resign from Rangers job: Former manager releases joint-statement with David Weir and Frank McParland|date=February 15, 2017|website=Irish Times|archive-url=https://archive.today/20180505142717/https://www.irishtimes.com/sport/soccer/mark-warburton-reiterates-he-did-not-resign-from-rangers-job-1.2976472|archivedate=5 May 2018|url-status=live|accessdate=May 5, 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Weir then assisted Warburton at [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]], but they were sacked on 31 December 2017.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/42528150 |title=Mark Warburton: Nottingham Forest sack manager after nine months in charge |publisher=BBC Sport |date=31 December 2017 |accessdate=31 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Brighton & Hove Albion===\nAs of April 2019, Weir was working for [[Brighton & Hove Albion F.C.|Brighton & Hove Albion]] in a role where he manages young players who are loaned out to foreign clubs.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.edinburghnews.scotsman.com/sport/football/hearts/latest-hearts-news/david-weir-recalls-last-time-hearts-won-two-derbies-in-one-season-at-easter-road-1-4913625 |title=David Weir recalls last time Hearts won two derbies in one season at Easter Road |work=Edinburgh Evening News |publisher= |date=24 April 2019 |accessdate=24 April 2019 |first=Barry |last=Anderson}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nAs of 2011, Weir and his wife Fiona had four children: Lucas, [[Jensen Weir|Jensen]], Kenzie and Ruben.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/former-everton-fc-defender-david-3364790 |title=Former Everton FC defender David Weir is ready to tell his story |newspaper=Liverpool Echo |publisher= |date=9 September 2011 |accessdate=21 February 2020}}</ref> Jensen is also a footballer who plays as a [[midfielder]]; born in [[Warrington]], he began his club career at [[Wigan Athletic F.C.|Wigan Athletic]] and played for both [[Scotland national under-17 football team|Scotland]] and [[England national under-17 football team|England]] at under-17 level.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scotsman.com/sport/football/david-weir-s-son-becomes-youngest-player-in-wigan-athletic-history-1-4608036|title=David Weir's son becomes youngest player in Wigan Athletic history|date=8 November 2017|accessdate=26 November 2017|author=David Gunn|work=The Scotsman}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n===International===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n! colspan=3 | [[Scotland national football team|Scotland national team]]<ref>{{SFA profile|id=15624|name=David Weir}}</ref>\n|-\n!Year!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n| 1997 || 3 || 0\n|-\n| 1998 || 6 || 0\n|-\n| 1999 || 10 || 0\n|-\n| 2000 || 5 || 0\n|-\n| 2001 || 6 || 1\n|-\n| 2002 || 7 || 0\n|-\n| 2003 || colspan=2|\u2014\n|-\n| 2004 || colspan=2|\u2014\n|-\n| 2005 || 8 || 0\n|-\n| 2006 || 7 || 0\n|-\n| 2007 || 9 || 0\n|-\n| 2008 || 2 || 0\n|-\n| 2009 || 2 || 0\n|-\n| 2010 || 4 || 0\n|-\n!Total || 69 || 1\n|}\n\n===Manager===\n{| class=wikitable style=\"text-align: center\"\n|+ Managerial record by team and tenure<ref>[http://www.soccerbase.com/managers/manager.sd?manager_id=2510 David Weir managerial statistics on Soccerbase]</ref>\n|-\n!rowspan=2|Team\n!rowspan=2|From\n!rowspan=2|To\n!colspan=5|Record\n|-\n!{{abbr|P|Matches played}}!!{{abbr|W|Matches won}}!!{{abbr|D|Matches drawn}}!!{{abbr|L|Matches lost}}!!{{abbr|Win %|Win percentage}}\n|-\n|align=left|[[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]]\n|align=left|10 June 2013\n|align=left|11 October 2013\n{{WDL|13|1|2|10|decimals=1}}\n|}\n\n==Honours==\n===Club===\n'''Falkirk'''\n* [[Scottish Challenge Cup]]: [[1993 Scottish Challenge Cup Final|1992\u201393]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football-falkirk-find-their-fire-1467272.html|title=Football: Falkirk find their fire|date=1993-12-13|work=The Independent|accessdate=2018-05-24|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n'''Heart of Midlothian'''\n* [[Scottish Cup]]: [[1998 Scottish Cup Final|1997\u201398]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.londonhearts.com/aamain/cup1998.htm|title=Sat 16 May 1998 Scottish Cup Final Heart Of Midlothian 2 Rangers 1|website=www.londonhearts.com|accessdate=2018-05-24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football-scottish-cup-final-stage-of-dramatic-hearts-1158932.html|title=Football: Scottish Cup Final: Stage of dramatic Hearts|date=1998-05-17|work=The Independent|accessdate=2018-05-24|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n'''Rangers''' \n*[[Scottish Premier League]]: [[2008\u201309 Scottish Premier League|2008\u201309]],<ref>{{ cite news | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/scot_prem/8062744.stm| publisher=BBC Sport| first=Andy |last=Campbell| date=24 May 2009 | title=Dundee United 0-3 Rangers}}</ref> [[2009\u201310 Scottish Premier League|2009\u201310]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/scot_prem/8638892.stm|title=Hibernian 0\u20131 Rangers|date=25 April 2010|publisher=BBC Sport | first=Andy |last=Campbell}}</ref> [[2010\u201311 Scottish Premier League|2010\u201311]]\n*Scottish Cup: [[2008 Scottish Cup Final|2007\u201308]],<ref>{{cite news |title=Queen of the South 2-3 Rangers|publisher=BBC Sport|date=24 May 2008| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/scot_cups/7416622.stm|first=Clive|last=Lindsay}}</ref> [[2009 Scottish Cup Final|2008\u201309]]<ref name=\"SC2009\">{{ cite news | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/scot_cups/8072822.stm | title=Rangers 1\u20130 Falkirk|first=Colin |last=Moffat | publisher=BBC Sport |date=30 May 2009}}</ref>\n*[[Scottish League Cup]]: [[2008 Scottish League Cup Final|2007\u201308]],<ref>{{cite news |title=Dundee Utd 2-2 Rangers|publisher=BBC Sport|date=16 March 2008| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/scot_cups/7296157.stm|first=Thomas |last=McGuigan}}</ref> [[2010 Scottish League Cup Final|2009\u201310]],<ref name=\"SLC2010\">{{cite news |title=St Mirren 0-1 Rangers|publisher=BBC Sport|date=21 March 2010| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/scot_cups/8576203.stm|first=Andy |last=Campbell}}</ref> [[2011 Scottish League Cup Final|2010\u201311]]\n\n===International===\n'''Scotland'''\n* [[Kirin Cup]]: 2006<ref>{{Cite news | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/internationals/4765811.stm| title=Japan 0-0 Scotland | publisher=BBC Sport| date=13 May 2006 }}</ref>\n\n===Individual===\n*[[SFWA Footballer of the Year]]: 2010<ref name=\"Weir wins writers' award\" />\n*[[2009\u201310 Scottish Premier League#Clydesdale Bank Premier League Awards|Scottish Premier League Player of the Year]]: 2010<ref name=\"Weir wins Clydesdale award\" />\n*[[List of Scottish Premier League monthly award winners#2009.E2.80.9310|Scottish Premier League Player of the Month]]: February 2010<ref name=\"Weir feb\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Soccerbase}}\n*[http://www.sporting-heroes.net/football-heroes/searchresults.asp?FootballHeroName=David+Weir Photos & stats] Sporting-Heroes.net\n*[http://www.londonhearts.com/scores/players/weirdavy.html Davy Weir profile] [http://www.londonhearts.com LondonHearts.com]\n\n{{Navboxes\n|title=Awards\n|bg=gold\n|fg=navy\n|list1=\n{{SFWA Footballer of the Year}}\n{{2009\u201310 PFA Scotland SPL Team of the Year}}\n{{Rangers F.C. Hall of Fame}}\n}}\n{{Scotland squad 1998 FIFA World Cup}}\n{{Sheffield United F.C. managers}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Weir, David}}\n[[Category:1970 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:All-American men's college soccer players]]\n[[Category:Scotland international footballers]]\n[[Category:Scottish footballers]]\n[[Category:Scottish Premier League players]]\n[[Category:Scottish Football League players]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Falkirk]]\n[[Category:Evansville Purple Aces men's soccer players]]\n[[Category:Association football central defenders]]\n[[Category:Falkirk F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Heart of Midlothian F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Everton F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Rangers F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Premier League players]]\n[[Category:1998 FIFA World Cup players]]\n[[Category:Scottish expatriate sportspeople in the United States]]\n[[Category:Scottish expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Scottish football managers]]\n[[Category:Sheffield United F.C. managers]]\n[[Category:English Football League managers]]\n[[Category:Everton F.C. non-playing staff]]\n[[Category:Brentford F.C. non-playing staff]]\n[[Category:Rangers F.C. non-playing staff]]\n[[Category:Nottingham Forest F.C. non-playing staff]]\n[[Category:Brighton & Hove Albion F.C. non-playing staff]]\n", "text_old": "{{Other people|David Weir}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2013}}\n{{infobox football biography\n| name            = David Weir\n| image           = David Weir 2014.jpg\n| caption         = Weir as [[Brentford F.C.|Brentford]] assistant in 2014\n| fullname        = David Gillespie Weir<ref name=\"Hugman2007\u201308 427\">{{Cite book\n | editor-first = Barry J.\n | editor-last = Hugman\n | title = The PFA Footballers' Who's Who 2007\u201308\n | year = 2007\n | publisher = Mainstream Publishing\n | isbn = 978-1-84596-246-3\n | page = 427 }}</ref>\n| birth_date      = {{Birth date and age|1970|5|10|df=y}}\n| birth_place     = [[Falkirk]], Scotland\n| height          = {{height|ft=6|in=3}}\n| currentclub     = \n| position        = [[Centre back]]\n| collegeyears1     = 1988\u20131992 | college1 = [[Evansville Purple Aces men's soccer|Evansville Purple Aces]]<ref name=\"Weir in US\"/>\n| years1          = 1992\u20131996 | clubs1 = [[Falkirk F.C.|Falkirk]]                         | caps1 = 133 | goals1 = 8\n| years2          = 1996\u20131999 | clubs2 = [[Heart of Midlothian F.C.|Heart of Midlothian]] | caps2 = 76  | goals2 = 6\n| years3          = 1999\u20132007 | clubs3 = [[Everton F.C.|Everton]]                         | caps3 = 235 | goals3 = 10\n| years4          = 2007\u20132012 | clubs4 = [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]]                         | caps4 = 162 | goals4 = 4\n| totalcaps       = 606 | totalgoals = 28\n| nationalyears1  = 1997\u20132010\n| nationalteam1 = [[Scotland national football team|Scotland]]\n| nationalcaps1  = 69\n| nationalgoals1 = 1\n| manageryears1   = 2013      | managerclubs1 = [[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]] \n}}\n'''David Gillespie Weir''' (born 10 May 1970) is a Scottish [[association football|football]] player and coach.\n\nBorn in [[Falkirk]], Weir played as a [[Defender (association football)|defender]], and began his professional career with his home-town club, [[Falkirk F.C.|Falkirk]], after having attended the [[University of Evansville]] in the United States. After four seasons with the Bairns, Weir then moved on to [[Heart of Midlothian F.C.|Heart of Midlothian]] where he won the [[1998 Scottish Cup Final|1998 Scottish Cup]]. He joined [[Everton F.C.|Everton]] in 1999 and spent seven years with the club, becoming club captain under two different managers. Weir then moved to Rangers in 2007 and became club captain after [[Barry Ferguson]] was stripped of the role in April 2009. Weir called time on his playing career in May 2012.\n\nWeir won his first [[cap (sport)|cap]] for the [[Scotland national football team]] in 1997 and was selected for their [[1998 FIFA World Cup]] squad. He retired from international football in 2002, when [[Berti Vogts]] was the manager, but returned when [[Walter Smith]] took charge in 2004. Weir became the oldest Scotland player when he played in [[UEFA Euro 2012 qualifying]] matches in 2010. He finished his international career with  69 [[Cap (sport)|caps]], which makes him  [[Scotland national football team records#Most capped players|Scotland's seventh-most capped player]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scottishfa.co.uk/scottish_football_players.cfm?page=138|title=International Roll of Honour|publisher=Scottish Football Association|accessdate=17 June 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101011104402/http://www.scottishfa.co.uk/scottish_football_players.cfm?page=138|archive-date=11 October 2010|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nWeir had a brief spell as manager of [[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]] in 2013. He has since assisted [[Mark Warburton]] at [[Brentford F.C.|Brentford]], [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]] and [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]].\n\n==Playing career==\n===Club===\n====Evansville Purple Aces====\nWeir was scouted by the [[University of Evansville]] during a schools festival in [[Grantham, Lincolnshire]]. He moved to the United States on a [[Sports scholarships|scholarship]] from 1988 to 1991.<ref name=\"Weir in US\" /> Whilst in [[Evansville, Indiana|Evansville]], he was converted from a centre back to a striker due to his lack of pace.<ref name=\"Weir in US\" /> Weir excelled in this position, scoring 28 goals in 27 matches during his [[Senior (education)|senior]] year. This form led to him being named an [[Division I First-Team All-American (soccer)|NCAA All-American]] and [[Midwest Collegiate Conference|Midwest Collegiate Conference Player of the Year]] in 1990.<ref name=\"Weir in US\">{{cite news\n| title = How Davie Weir wowed the Yanks\n| url = http://www.newsoftheworld.co.uk/scottish/scottish_sport/772766/Fred-Schmalz-reveals-Gers-ace-was-too-slow-to-be-a-defender.html\n| work = News of the World\n| date = 4 April 2010}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gopurpleaces.com/news/2014/4/21/MSOC_0421142355.aspx|title=Former UE Soccer Standout Weir Helps Brentford to Promotion|publisher=}}</ref> Weir is tied for the school record with 50 career goals and ranks second in school history with 129 career points.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n====Falkirk====\nUpon returning from the United States Weir trained with [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]]; however, he did not sign a professional contract. In 1992, he joined then [[Scottish Football League First Division|Scottish First Division]] side [[Falkirk F.C.|Falkirk]] and went on to make 134 appearances for the club and score eight goals. He was part of the side which won promotion to the Scottish Premier Division. Weir also won the [[1993 Scottish Challenge Cup Final|1993 Scottish Challenge Cup]] on 12 December, playing in the side that defeated [[St Mirren F.C.|St Mirren]] 3\u20130 at [[Fir Park]] in [[Motherwell]].<ref>{{Cite news |first=David |last=McKinney |title=Football: Falkirk find their fire |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football-falkirk-find-their-fire-1467272.html |work=The Independent |location=London |date=13 December 1993 |accessdate=21 March 2015  }}</ref>\n\n====Heart of Midlothian====\nOn 30 June 1996, Weir moved to Premier Division side [[Heart of Midlothian F.C.|Heart of Midlothian]]. He made his debut for the club in a [[Scottish League Cup|League Cup]] match against [[Stenhousemuir F.C.|Stenhousemuir]] on 14 August 1996 and scored his first goal three days later. Weir netted Hearts second goal in a 3\u20132 win over [[Kilmarnock F.C.|Kilmarnock]]. His first sending off was in an infamous game against [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]] at [[Ibrox Stadium|Ibrox]] on 14 September 1996. Rangers won the match 3\u20130 but Hearts had four players ordered off in a twenty-minute spell.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.soccerbase.com/results3.sd?gameid=241789 | title=Rangers 3 (1) \u2013 0 (0) Hearts| work=Soccerbase | accessdate= 14 September 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/hearts-face-inquiry-into-ibrox-fracas-1363509.html | title=Hearts face inquiry into Ibrox fracas | work=The Independent | accessdate=16 September 2010 | location=London | first=David | last=McKinney | date=16 September 1996}}</ref>\n\nWeir won his second career honour, the [[1998 Scottish Cup Final|1998 Scottish Cup]], by beating Rangers 2\u20131 in the final at [[Celtic Park]]. He left [[Tynecastle Stadium|Tynecastle]] midway through the following season when he was purchased by Everton for \u00a3250,000. Weir played 116 games in all for Hearts and scored twelve goals.\n\n====Everton====\nWeir joined [[Everton F.C.|Everton]] on 16 February 1999 and made his debut in a league match against [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]] the next day as Everton won, 5\u20130, coming on as a substitute for [[John Oster]] after 73 minutes.<ref>{{Cite news | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/sport/football/scottish_league/280417.stm | title=Weir flies south | publisher=BBC Sport | date=16 February 1999}}</ref> Weir's first goal for Everton was a last-minute equaliser against [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]] in a 4\u20134 draw in October 1998. At the end of the 2001\u201302 season, Weir was voted Everton's Player of the Year by planetfootball's readers, with Weir the only player to reach four figures in terms of votes.<ref>{{cite news|title=King David|url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11671/2237033/|publisher=Sky Sports|date=10 May 2002|accessdate=5 June 2013}}</ref> In the [[Merseyside derby]] match on 19 April 2003, Weir received his first red card for the club as Everton lost 2\u20131 and played with 9 men after [[Gary Naysmith]] was also sent off.\n\nHe had a very successful time with the Merseyside club, playing regularly for eight years, making 269 appearances (scoring 10 goals in the process), playing in European competition, becoming club captain under two different managers \u2013 [[Walter Smith]] and [[David Moyes]] \u2013 and winning the bulk of his Scotland caps on the strength of his performances for the Toffees. During the 2005\u201306 season, his side played in [[2005\u201306 UEFA Champions League|UEFA Champions League]] but lost 4\u20132 on aggregate to Spanish side [[Villarreal CF]] in the third qualifying round. After being eliminated in the Champions League, Everton played in the [[2005\u201306 UEFA Cup|UEFA Cup]] but lost again, this time to Romanian side [[FC Dinamo Bucure\u0219ti|Dinamo Bucure\u0219ti]] 5\u20132 on aggregate in the first round of UEFA Cup.\n\n====Rangers====\nOn 16 January 2007, Weir signed for Rangers on an initial six-month deal after Everton released him from his contract early. He teamed up again with former manager Walter Smith.<ref name=\"Weir completes switch to Rangers\">{{cite news\n| title = Weir completes switch to Rangers\n| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/r/rangers/6262693.stm\n| publisher=BBC Sport \n| date = 16 January 2007}}</ref> He made his Rangers debut against [[Dunfermline Athletic F.C.|Dunfermline Athletic]] on 21 January 2007.<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Dunfermline 0\u20131 Rangers\n| url = http://newsimg.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/scot_prem/6277399.stm\n| publisher=BBC Sport \n| first=Thomas |last=McGuigan\n| date = 21 January 2007}}</ref>\nHis performances for the Glasgow club were enough to secure a one-year contract. After his man-of-the-match performance against [[St Mirren F.C.|St Mirren]] on 8 April 2007, he revealed that he may remain at [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]] for the [[2007\u201308 in Scottish football|2007\u201308 season]] after discussing the issue with his family. His agent met with Rangers on 19 April to discuss a possible extension to his contract, which was due to expire at the end of that season. Weir signed a one-year extension to his deal, keeping him at Rangers until the summer of 2008.<ref>{{cite news\n|title = Weir signs one-year deal at Ibrox|url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/r/rangers/6562919.stm|publisher=BBC Sport |date = 20 April 2007}}</ref>\n\nHe scored his first Rangers goal against [[FK Zeta]] in a [[UEFA Champions League]] qualifier, on 31 July 2007.<ref name=\"Rangers 2-0 FK Zeta\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/europe/6922795.stm|publisher=BBC Sport|title=Rangers 2\u20130 FK Zeta |date=31 July 2007|first=Colin|last=Moffat}}</ref> Weir was highly praised for his endurance during the 2007\u201308 season as Rangers chased [[The Quadruple]]. Despite being in his late 30s, he managed sixty appearances that season and produced some outstanding performances alongside [[Carlos Cu\u00e9llar]] in the centre of defence. Weir won his third and fourth trophies of his career in 2008, as Rangers claimed [[Scottish Cup]] and [[Scottish League Cup|League Cup]] glory. On 3 July he signed a further one-year contract extension to his deal.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/r/rangers/7487125.stm|title=Veteran duo seal new Ibrox deals|date=3 July 2008|publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref> He was appointed Rangers' captain on 3 April 2009 after [[Barry Ferguson]] had been stripped the role following an incident whilst on international duty. Weir won the [[2008\u201309 Scottish Premier League|League]] and [[Scottish Cup|Cup]] double in season [[2008\u201309 Rangers F.C. season|2008\u201309]] with Rangers and signed a further one-year contract extension which saw playing into his forties.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/r/rangers/8077300.stm|title=Weir poised for new Rangers deal |date=1 June 2009|publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/r/rangers/8134602.stm|title=Weir not pondering his retirement|date=4 July 2009|publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref> In March 2010, Weir won the [[Scottish Premier League monthly awards|Player of the month award]] for February<ref name=\"Weir feb\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/r/rangers/8555925.stm|title=Rangers' Weir wins February award|date=8 March 2010|publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref> and followed this up with the Clydesdale Bank Premier League Player of the Year award for the 2009\u201310 season.<ref name=\"Weir wins Clydesdale award\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/scot_prem/8630065.stm|title=Rangers duo win Clydesdale manager and player awards |date=19 April 2010|publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref> On 7 May 2010 it was announced Weir had also won the [[SFWA Footballer of the Year|Scottish Football Writers' Association Footballer of the Year Award]], the oldest player ever to receive this accolade \u2013 just three days before his 40th birthday.<ref name=\"Weir wins writers' award\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/r/rangers/8667560.stm|title=Rangers captain David Weir wins writers' award|date=7 May 2010|publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref> Soon afterwards, Weir agreed another one-year contract which saw him play on into his forties.<ref>{{Cite news | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/r/rangers/8777141.stm | title=David Weir agrees new Rangers contract  | date=30 June 2010 | accessdate=22 September 2011 | publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref> He became the third oldest player ever to compete in the [[UEFA Champions League]] on 14 September 2010 in Rangers' 0-0 away draw with [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] at [[Old Trafford]] and he became the joint oldest outfield player in Champions League history when he played against Bursaspor in December 2010, aged 40 years 211 days.<ref>{{cite news|last=Pattullo |first=Alan |url=http://sport.scotsman.com/sport/David-Weir-joins--.6651998.jp|title=David Weir joins lofty company as oldest player to grace Champions League |work=The Scotsman|date=7 December 2010 |accessdate=22 February 2011}}</ref> Weir captured his third league title with Rangers as captain on the week of his 41st birthday when Rangers defeated Kilmarnock 5-1 on the last day of the season beating Celtic to the title by a single point.\n\nOn 26 May 2011, it was announced that Weir was to be inducted into the [[Rangers F.C. Hall of Fame]]. He has become the first ever player to be inducted into the Hall of Fame whilst under contract at the club.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportinglife.com/football/scottishpremier/news/story_get.cgi?STORY_NAME=soccer/11/05/26/SOCCER_Rangers_Weir.html&TEAMHD=scotspremiership&BID=425 |title=Weir Revels in Hall of Fame Honour |work=Sporting Life |accessdate=31 August 2011 }}{{dead link|date=December 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> On 17 July 2011, Weir signed a new one-year deal with Rangers.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/14177444.stm?|title=Rangers captain David Weir signs one-year deal at Ibrox |publisher=BBC Sport|date=17 July 2011 | accessdate=11 August 2011 }}</ref> Following Walter Smith's retirement as manager, [[Ally McCoist]] succeeded him. Under McCoist, Weir did not play in the League, and he was replaced as captain by [[Steven Davis]]. Weir made his last appearance in the Champions' League Third qualifying round 1st leg against Swedish side [[Malm\u00f6 FF]]. Weir played for 29 minutes, before being replaced by [[Juan Manuel Ortiz]].\n\nOn 17 January 2012, he announced that he would be leaving Rangers in order to continue his career at an unnamed club in England. The club he was close to signing for was [[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]] and he trained with the Blades for several weeks, however he moved into coaching instead.<ref name=\"Weir poised for job\">{{cite news|title=David Weir poised for job as Sheffield United boss|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/22833212|accessdate=10 June 2013|publisher=BBC Sport|date=9 June 2013}}</ref>\n\n=== International ===\nWeir earned his first [[cap (football)|cap]] for [[Scotland national football team|Scotland]] in a 1\u20130 defeat to [[Wales national football team|Wales]] on 27 May 1997.<ref name=\"Scotland v Wales\">{{cite news\n |title        = Scotland v Wales\n |url          = http://www.scottishfa.co.uk/match_details.cfm?matchid=57898\n |publisher    = Scottish FA\n |date         = 14 November 2007\n |access-date  = 14 November 2007\n |archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20071204072528/http://www.scottishfa.co.uk/match_details.cfm?matchid=57898\n |archive-date = 4 December 2007\n |url-status     = dead\n |df           = dmy-all\n}}</ref> He scored his one and only goal for Scotland in [[FIFA World Cup qualification|a World Cup qualifier]] against [[Latvia national football team|Latvia]] at [[Hampden Park]] on 6 October 2001.<ref name=\"Scotland v Latvia\">{{cite news\n| title = Scots out with a whimper\n| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/world_cup_2002/1576720.stm\n| publisher = BBC Sport\n| accessdate = 21 September 2011\n| date = 6 October 2001}}</ref>\n\nWeir temporarily retired from international football in 2002 after his performance in a [[UEFA Euro 2004 qualifying]] match against the [[Faroe Islands national football team|Faroe Islands]] was criticised by manager [[Berti Vogts]].<ref>{{Cite news | url=http://newsvote.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/internationals/scotland/2232138.stm?dynamic_vote=ON#vote_vogts_07_09_2002 | title=Lucky Scots scrape draw in Faroes| publisher=BBC Sport | date=7 September 2002}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news | url=http://sport.scotsman.com/football/Weir-I-was-right-to.2381553.jp | title=Weir: I was right to quit Scotland | work=The Scotsman | date=27 November 2002}}</ref> He returned to international football when Walter Smith was appointed Scotland manager in December 2004.\n\nWeir became a member of the [[Scotland national football team roll of honour]] when he won his 50th Scotland cap. This milestone came in a match against [[Lithuania national football team|Lithuania]] on 6 September 2006, in which he captained his country to a 2\u20131 win.<ref name=\"Lithuania v Scotland\">{{cite news\n |title        = Lithuania v Scotland\n |url          = http://www.scottishfa.co.uk/match_details.cfm?matchid=58167\n |publisher    = Scottish FA\n |date         = 14 November 2007\n |access-date  = 21 January 2012\n |archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20071204072532/http://www.scottishfa.co.uk/match_details.cfm?matchid=58167\n |archive-date = 4 December 2007\n |url-status     = dead\n |df           = dmy-all\n}}</ref> He  captained Scotland four times.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scottishfa.co.uk/international_fixture_details.cfm?page=32&matchID=58167|title=Lithuania vs Scotland Match Report|publisher=Scottish FA|accessdate=31 August 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scottishfa.co.uk/international_fixture_details.cfm?page=32&matchID=62498|title=Scotland vs Faroe Islands Match Report|publisher=Scottish FA|accessdate=31 August 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scottishfa.co.uk/international_fixture_details.cfm?page=32&matchID=55680|title=Japan vs Scotland Match Report|publisher=Scottish FA|accessdate=31 August 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scottishfa.co.uk/international_fixture_details.cfm?page=32&matchID=55681|title=Bulgaria vs Scotland Match Report|publisher=Scottish FA|accessdate=31 August 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 August 2010, Weir was recalled to the Scotland squad at the age of 40 for the [[UEFA Euro 2012 qualifying|Euro 2012]] qualifying matches against [[Lithuania national football team|Lithuania]] and [[Liechtenstein national football team|Liechtenstein]] in September 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/news/story?id=817106&sec=euro2012&cc=5739|title=Scotland recall for 40-year-old Weir|date=24 August 2010|work=ESPN Soccernet}}</ref> Weir became the oldest ever Scottish football international when he played against Lithuania on 3 September 2010, aged 40 years and 116 days, breaking [[Jim Leighton]]'s previous record of 40 years and 78 days.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/scotland/8955170.stm |title=David Weir set for Scotland milestone |date=3 September 2010|publisher = BBC Sport}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/match/3118708 |title=Lithuania v Scotland Match facts |date=3 September 2010 |work=The Guardian |location=London}}</ref><ref name=rsssoldyoung>[http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/oldest-youngest.html Oldest and Youngest Players and Goal-scorers in International Football], [[RSSSF]], 20 September 2018</ref>\n\n==Coaching and management==\n\n===Everton coach===\nIn February 2012, Weir returned to Everton in a coaching capacity with the club's academy and reserve teams. He made his reserve-team debut for the club against [[Liverpool F.C. Reserves and Academy|Liverpool]] on the day of his return.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.evertonfc.com/news/archive/2012/02/21/weir-back-with-blues|title=Weir Back With Blues|publisher=Everton F.C.|accessdate=21 February 2012|date=21 February 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120326054517/http://www.evertonfc.com/news/archive/2012/02/21/weir-back-with-blues|archive-date=26 March 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> When manager [[David Moyes]] left the club to replace [[Alex Ferguson|Sir Alex Ferguson]] at Manchester United in May 2013, Weir was interviewed by [[Bill Kenwright]] for the vacant role at Everton, but the job instead went to [[Roberto Mart\u00ednez]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2013/may/30/roberto-martinez-everton-second-interview|title=Roberto Mart\u00ednez set for second interview for Everton manager's job|work=The Guardian|accessdate=5 June 2013|date=5 June 2013|location=London|first=Andy|last=Hunter}}</ref>\n\n===Sheffield United manager===\nIn June 2013, Weir signed a three-year deal to manage [[Football League One|League One]] side [[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]].<ref name=\"Blades appoint Weir\">{{cite news|title=David Weir: Sheffield United appoint Everton coach as boss|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/22843168|accessdate=10 June 2013|publisher=BBC Sport|date=10 June 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"guardian appointment\">{{cite news|title=David Weir is appointed new Sheffield United manager on three-year deal|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2013/jun/10/sheffield-united-david-weir|accessdate=10 June 2013|work=The Guardian|date=10 June 2013|location=London}}</ref>  Despite winning his first competitive game in charge, a 2\u20131 victory over [[Notts County F.C.|Notts County]], United struggled under his management and failed to win any of their following twelve matches, leading to growing pressure from the club's fans for Weir to be sacked.<ref name=\"enjoying bdtbl\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thestar.co.uk/sport/sheffield-united/sheffield-united-why-weir-is-still-loving-life-at-the-lane-1-6093667|title=Why Weir is still loving life at the Lane|work=The Sheffield Star|accessdate=29 September 2013|date=28 September 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131001133534/http://www.thestar.co.uk/sport/sheffield-united/sheffield-united-why-weir-is-still-loving-life-at-the-lane-1-6093667|archive-date=1 October 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref>  After United were beaten at home by [[Football League Two|League Two]] side [[Hartlepool United F.C.|Hartlepool United]], eliminating them from the [[Football League Trophy]], Weir was sacked on 11 October 2013.<ref name=\"blades exit\">{{cite web|url=http://www.sufc.co.uk/news/article/20131011-weir-departs-1110494.aspx|title=Manager Weir departs as Blades Boss|publisher=Sheffield United F.C.|date=11 October 2013|accessdate=11 October 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Assistant to Mark Warburton===\nFollowing the departure of caretaker [[Alan Kernaghan]], Weir was appointed as [[Mark Warburton]]'s assistant manager at League One side [[Brentford F.C.|Brentford]] on 16 December 2013.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/25400456 |title=Brentford: David Weir joins as Kernaghan and Farrell leave |publisher=BBC Sport |date=16 December 2013 |accessdate=16 December 2013}}</ref> After a successful season which saw Brentford promoted to the [[Football League Championship|Championship]], Weir signed a new one-year rolling contract to remain with the [[Griffin Park]] club.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.getwestlondon.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/brentford-manager-agrees-new-contract-7331786|title=Brentford manager agrees new contract|first=Jacob|last=Murtagh|date=26 June 2014|publisher=}}</ref> On 17 February 2015, it was announced that Weir, Warburton and Sporting Director Frank McParland would leave Brentford at the end of the [[2014\u201315 Brentford F.C. season|2014\u201315]] season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.brentfordfc.co.uk/news/article/brentford-fc-mark-warburton-frank-mcparland-david-weir-statement-2277027.aspx|title=Brentford FC club statement 17.02.2015|work= |publisher=Brentford FC}}</ref>\n\nOn 15 June 2015, Weir returned to Rangers on a three-year deal to assist Warburton.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rangers.co.uk/news/headlines/item/9468-warburton-appointed-manager |title=Warburton Appointed Manager |work=Rangers |publisher=rangers.co.uk |date=15 June 2015 |accessdate=15 June 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150618003515/http://www.rangers.co.uk/news/headlines/item/9468-warburton-appointed-manager |archivedate=18 June 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Weir and Warburton extended their contracts with Rangers by a further year in July 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|title =Rangers: Mark Warburton completes contract extension |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/36770547 |publisher=BBC Sport|date=12 July 2016|accessdate=18 November 2016}}</ref> In February 2017 Rangers released an official statement claiming that Weir, Warburton and head of recruitment Frank McParland had resigned their positions, effective immediately.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://rangers.co.uk/news/headlines/club-statement-74/ |title=Club Statement |work= |publisher=Rangers F.C. |date=10 February 2017 |accessdate=10 February 2017}}</ref> This was denied in a joint statement by all three men, but their tenure at the club had nonetheless come to an end.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/sport/soccer/mark-warburton-reiterates-he-did-not-resign-from-rangers-job-1.2976472|title=Mark Warburton reiterates he did not resign from Rangers job: Former manager releases joint-statement with David Weir and Frank McParland|date=February 15, 2017|website=Irish Times|archive-url=https://archive.today/20180505142717/https://www.irishtimes.com/sport/soccer/mark-warburton-reiterates-he-did-not-resign-from-rangers-job-1.2976472|archivedate=5 May 2018|url-status=live|accessdate=May 5, 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Weir then assisted Warburton at [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]], but they were sacked on 31 December 2017.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/42528150 |title=Mark Warburton: Nottingham Forest sack manager after nine months in charge |publisher=BBC Sport |date=31 December 2017 |accessdate=31 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Brighton & Hove Albion===\nAs of April 2019, Weir was working for [[Brighton & Hove Albion F.C.|Brighton & Hove Albion]] in a role where he manages young players who are loaned out to foreign clubs.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.edinburghnews.scotsman.com/sport/football/hearts/latest-hearts-news/david-weir-recalls-last-time-hearts-won-two-derbies-in-one-season-at-easter-road-1-4913625 |title=David Weir recalls last time Hearts won two derbies in one season at Easter Road |work=Edinburgh Evening News |publisher= |date=24 April 2019 |accessdate=24 April 2019 |first=Barry |last=Anderson}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nAs of 2011, Weir and his wife Fiona had four children: Lucas, [[Jensen Weir|Jensen]], Kenzie and Ruben.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/former-everton-fc-defender-david-3364790 |title=Former Everton FC defender David Weir is ready to tell his story |newspaper=Liverpool Echo |publisher= |date=9 September 2011 |accessdate=21 February 2020}}</ref> Jensen is also a footballer who plays as a [[midfielder]]; born in [[Warrington]], he began his club career at [[Wigan Athletic F.C.|Wigan Athletic]] and played for both [[Scotland national under-17 football team|Scotland]] and [[England national under-17 football team|England]] at under- 17 level.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scotsman.com/sport/football/david-weir-s-son-becomes-youngest-player-in-wigan-athletic-history-1-4608036|title=David Weir's son becomes youngest player in Wigan Athletic history|date=8 November 2017|accessdate=26 November 2017|author=David Gunn|work=The Scotsman}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n===International===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n! colspan=3 | [[Scotland national football team|Scotland national team]]<ref>{{SFA profile|id=15624|name=David Weir}}</ref>\n|-\n!Year!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n| 1997 || 3 || 0\n|-\n| 1998 || 6 || 0\n|-\n| 1999 || 10 || 0\n|-\n| 2000 || 5 || 0\n|-\n| 2001 || 6 || 1\n|-\n| 2002 || 7 || 0\n|-\n| 2003 || colspan=2|\u2014\n|-\n| 2004 || colspan=2|\u2014\n|-\n| 2005 || 8 || 0\n|-\n| 2006 || 7 || 0\n|-\n| 2007 || 9 || 0\n|-\n| 2008 || 2 || 0\n|-\n| 2009 || 2 || 0\n|-\n| 2010 || 4 || 0\n|-\n!Total || 69 || 1\n|}\n\n===Manager===\n{| class=wikitable style=\"text-align: center\"\n|+ Managerial record 